clinical_note: Susan Green is an 8-year-old girl referred by Dr. Christopher Lee for further evaluation of behavioral and developmental concerns consistent with childhood disintegrative-type autism spectrum features. Parents report that Susan had an initial period of relatively typical early development, followed by a notable regression beginning in early childhood, with loss of previously acquired language and social skills. Current concerns include markedly reduced social interaction, limited eye contact, and diminished interest in peer relationships. She exhibits repetitive behaviors, rigid routines, and significant difficulty with transitions. Teachers and parents describe unusual and disruptive behaviors, including episodes of agitation, self-directed vocalizations without clear communicative intent, and atypical responses to sensory stimuli (e.g., covering ears in response to ordinary sounds, distress with changes in clothing textures). There are also concerns about variable attention and occasional unexplained behavioral outbursts that are not clearly triggered by environmental factors. No prior genetic or metabolic testing has been documented. Family history is notable for a maternal cousin diagnosed with an autism spectrum condition in early childhood, with ongoing social communication difficulties and special education needs. In addition, a paternal grandfather reportedly had late-onset Alzheimer-type dementia, and a maternal aunt has long-standing rheumatoid arthritis. There is no known history of consanguinity. No other significant hereditary neurological or developmental disorders have been reported in the family.

Matthew Wright is a 12-year-old patient referred by Dr. Angela Thompson for further evaluation in the setting of multiple structural anomalies, developmental concerns, and neurological symptoms. Congenital findings include abnormal skull and facial shape noted since infancy, with persistent craniofacial asymmetry and atypical head contour on physical examination, raising concern for an underlying disorder of cranial or skeletal development. Developmentally, Matthew has a history of significant delays across multiple domains; he walked and talked later than expected and currently demonstrates moderate limitations in intellectual functioning and adaptive skills, requiring special education services and support with activities of daily living consistent with a moderate degree of cognitive impairment. Neurologically, he has a diagnosis of focal epilepsy with impairment of consciousness and intractable seizures, with episodes characterized by focal onset progressing to bilateral tonic-clonic activity and prolonged postictal confusion, despite treatment with multiple antiseizure medications. No significant family history is reported, and there is no known parental consanguinity. Prior genetic evaluation includes a single-gene test performed on 2025-01-07, which was negative and did not identify a molecular diagnosis.

Mark Young is a 14-year-old intersex patient who presents for evaluation with a history of childhood-onset autism spectrum disorder characterized by significant social communication difficulties, restricted interests, and repetitive behaviors. Caregivers report persistent challenges in reciprocal social interaction, limited eye contact, and difficulty understanding social cues at home and in school settings. Behaviorally, Mark exhibits rigid routines, intense preoccupation with specific topics, and marked distress with changes in schedule, as well as episodic behavioral dysregulation including irritability and occasional aggressive outbursts when overstimulated or frustrated. Teachers have documented ongoing concerns regarding atypical behaviors and emotional regulation in the classroom, including difficulties with transitions, sensory sensitivities (particularly to noise and crowded environments), and episodes of withdrawal or agitation in overstimulating settings. There is no prior documented genetic or metabolic testing in the chart, and no previous neuroimaging or targeted molecular studies are recorded. Family history is notable for a younger brother diagnosed with autism spectrum disorder with similar social and behavioral challenges, and a maternal uncle with a history of learning and behavioral difficulties requiring special education services, though he never underwent formal diagnostic evaluation. No additional significant family history of neurodegenerative disease, major congenital anomalies, or known hereditary syndromes is documented.

Anthony Sanchez (DOB: 11/20/2024) is a young child referred by Dr. Michael Smith for evaluation of behavioral and developmental concerns. Caregivers report features consistent with an autism spectrum disorder, including limited eye contact, reduced social reciprocity, and restricted interests, with atypical responses to sensory stimuli. There are associated concerns for delayed motor coordination and fine motor skills, with difficulty with age-appropriate tasks such as grasping small objects and delayed achievement of gross motor milestones, raising concern for a coexisting developmental coordination disorder. Caregivers also describe intermittent episodes concerning for possible focal seizures with impaired awareness, characterized by brief staring spells and unresponsiveness, occasionally followed by post-event confusion, without clear generalized convulsions reported to date. No prior genetic or metabolic testing has been documented. Family history is notable for a maternal uncle diagnosed with epilepsy in childhood requiring long-term antiseizure medication, and a paternal cousin with a childhood-onset social-communication disorder and learning difficulties requiring special education services. Parents report that they are distant relatives from the same small town, and consanguinity is acknowledged at the level of second cousins. No additional significant family history of other neurologic, developmental, or congenital conditions has been reported.

Christopher Martin (DOB 2017-11-03) is a pediatric patient referred for further evaluation due to a history of multiple structural and developmental concerns. He has been noted to have features consistent with an underlying skeletal or connective tissue disorder, including disproportionate growth and abnormal skeletal development, raising concern for a congenital bone or cartilage dysplasia. Developmentally, he demonstrates significant delays across multiple domains, with late attainment of gross motor milestones (e.g., delayed independent walking), fine motor incoordination, and expressive and receptive language delays, along with ongoing concerns for impaired adaptive functioning at home and in school settings. Neurologically, he has a history of recurrent unprovoked seizures without a clearly identified etiology, with events described as generalized convulsive episodes associated with loss of consciousness and postictal confusion; seizure control has been variable despite standard antiseizure management. In addition, there are broader neurodevelopmental concerns, including difficulties with social communication, atypical play, and behavioral dysregulation that have not been fully characterized but raise concern for a complex neurodevelopmental disorder. No significant family history is reported, and there is no known parental consanguinity. Prior genetic evaluation has included single-gene testing performed on 2025-04-12, which was reported as negative.

Thomas Martin is a young child who presents for evaluation with a history of multiple structural anomalies noted since infancy, including abnormal head shape and craniofacial asymmetry consistent with plagiocephaly, with associated concerns about skull and facial alignment and need for ongoing monitoring of cranial growth and development. Caregivers and early intervention providers report significant global developmental delay, with markedly limited expressive language, delayed attainment of gross and fine motor milestones, and reduced adaptive functioning for age, consistent with a severe level of developmental impairment; he currently requires extensive support for basic activities and ongoing specialized therapies. Neurologically, he has experienced recurrent seizure-like episodes characterized by generalized tonic-clonic activity without a clearly identified etiology to date, and he is being followed for possible epilepsy; events have been described as unprovoked and not clearly associated with fever or acute illness, and there is concern for an underlying neurological disorder. He also has a documented history of a superficial neck injury involving the anterior cervical region, which has healed without reported long-term functional compromise but is noted in his record due to prior medical attention for that event. No significant family history is reported, including no known similarly affected relatives and no known consanguinity. Prior genetic evaluation has included a single-gene test performed on 2025-09-30, which was reported as negative and did not identify a causative variant explaining his clinical presentation.

George Taylor is a 13-year-old patient referred by Dr. Karen White for further evaluation of a complex clinical presentation that includes multiple structural anomalies, developmental concerns, and neurologic findings. Since early childhood, caregivers have reported the presence of several congenital anomalies involving more than one organ system, though no unifying diagnosis has been established to date. In addition, George has a history of mild intellectual impairment with global delays in achieving developmental milestones, including later-than-expected acquisition of expressive language and academic skills; current school performance is below grade level, and he receives special education services and speech/occupational therapy. Neurologically, he exhibits a progressive gait disturbance characterized by imbalance and clumsiness, with difficulty running and frequent falls, suggestive of a spinocerebellar ataxia pattern; there are no clear focal motor deficits, but coordination is notably impaired on tandem walking and finger-to-nose testing. Prior genetic evaluation has included a single-gene analysis performed on 02/22/2025, which was reported as negative and did not identify a causative variant to explain the observed congenital anomalies, developmental delay, or ataxic features. No significant family history is reported, and there is no known parental consanguinity.

Barbara Johnson is a 19-year-old female who presents for evaluation due to a history notable for multiple structural anomalies identified in childhood, involving more than one organ system and raising concern for an underlying syndromic condition. She has longstanding delays across developmental domains, including delayed attainment of early motor milestones and persistent academic and adaptive challenges consistent with global developmental delay; formal cognitive testing has documented below-age-expected functioning, and she continues to require educational supports and accommodations. Neurologically, she has unexplained abnormal movements characterized by intermittent involuntary posturing and muscle contractions affecting the upper extremities and neck, occurring both at rest and with action, without a clear precipitating event or exposure history; these episodes have been variably described as dystonic and have not been fully explained by prior neurologic evaluations. There is no additional significant systemic history documented beyond these findings. Prior genetic workup includes chromosomal microarray performed on 09/15/2025, which was reported as negative, with no pathogenic copy number variants or clinically significant chromosomal abnormalities identified. No significant family history is reported, and there is no known consanguinity.

Jennifer Scott is a 12-year-old female who presents for evaluation of longstanding social-communication concerns and behavioral differences consistent with an autism spectrum disorder, initially recognized in early childhood. Parents report limited eye contact, difficulty initiating and sustaining peer relationships, restricted interests, and sensory sensitivities (particularly to loud sounds and certain clothing textures). There is a history of atypical play patterns, insistence on routines, and significant distress with changes in schedule. School reports describe challenges with reciprocal conversation, understanding social cues, and group work, as well as occasional behavioral outbursts when routines are disrupted. She has required school-based supports, including an individualized education plan focused on social skills and classroom accommodations. Feeding difficulties have been noted since toddler years, characterized by strong food selectivity based on texture and color and prolonged mealtimes; although her growth parameters are currently appropriate, her dietary variety remains limited and her parents report ongoing concern about her restrictive eating patterns. Family history is notable for a younger brother diagnosed with an autism spectrum disorder with similar social-communication difficulties and restricted interests, as well as a maternal uncle who was described as “socially awkward” with learning challenges and who required special education services during childhood, though no formal diagnosis was documented. Parents report that they are second cousins, and there is awareness of distant relatives with developmental and behavioral concerns on both sides of the family. No prior genetic or metabolic testing has been documented in the record.

Donna Carter is a 10-year-old female who presents with longstanding concerns for social communication difficulties and behavioral rigidity consistent with an autism spectrum–type presentation, with onset in early childhood. According to her caregivers, she demonstrates limited eye contact, difficulty engaging in reciprocal conversations, and challenges in forming and maintaining age-appropriate peer relationships. She exhibits restricted interests and repetitive behaviors, including insistence on strict routines and significant distress with transitions or unexpected changes. Teachers have reported problems with attention and impulsivity, including difficulty sustaining focus on classroom tasks, frequent fidgeting, and interrupting others, raising concern for co-occurring attention and behavioral regulation difficulties. Academic performance is variable, with particular challenges in organization and task completion despite average skills in some areas, and she requires additional support in the school setting. There is no history of seizures, focal neurological deficits, or acute neurologic events documented in the available records. Family history is notable for a maternal uncle diagnosed in childhood with an autism spectrum condition characterized by social communication challenges and repetitive behaviors, currently living independently with some support, and a paternal grandfather with a history of early-onset coronary artery disease requiring stent placement in his 40s. No consanguinity has been reported. No prior genetic or other specialized diagnostic testing is documented in the chart.

James Rodriguez (DOB 02/24/2006) is an intersex individual referred by Dr. Daniel Jackson for genetic evaluation in the setting of longstanding concerns for a childhood-onset social communication disorder consistent with an autism spectrum presentation accompanied by features that raise concern for a more complex neurobehavioral etiology. According to caregiver and school reports, James has had persistent qualitative impairments in social reciprocity, including limited eye contact, difficulty understanding social cues, and challenges in forming and maintaining peer relationships, as well as restricted interests and repetitive behaviors. There is a history of behavioral rigidity, sensory sensitivities, and episodes of marked inattention and poor concentration documented in the educational setting, with teachers reporting fluctuating alertness and difficulty sustaining focus during academic tasks. These cognitive and attentional concerns have contributed to academic underperformance and the need for individualized educational supports. Family history is notable for a younger brother diagnosed in early childhood with a similar autism spectrum presentation characterized by social communication difficulties and restricted interests, and a maternal male cousin with learning difficulties requiring special education services, though no formal diagnostic workup is known for the cousin. The parents report that they are second cousins, and there are no known pregnancies affected by recurrent miscarriage, stillbirth, or early neonatal death. No prior genetic or metabolic testing has been documented in the available records.

William Brown is a 14-year-old individual with a history notable for multiple structural and neurodevelopmental concerns. He has been followed for a malformation of brain development characterized on prior neuroimaging as a nonspecific cerebral malformation, with abnormal cortical organization and concerns for an underlying disorder of brain development. Developmentally, he has exhibited significant delays since early childhood, with late attainment of major motor and language milestones and persistent global delay in adaptive, social, and academic functioning. School reports and prior developmental evaluations describe ongoing difficulties with expressive and receptive language, fine and gross motor coordination, and learning, requiring individualized educational support and related therapies. Neurologically, he has experienced intermittent abnormal movements and tone abnormalities consistent with a childhood-onset movement disorder, including episodes of increased tone and dystonic posturing, as well as periods of hypotonia in infancy, raising concern for an underlying central motor pathway disturbance. There is no reported history of similar neurodevelopmental or structural brain conditions in first- or second-degree relatives, and no known consanguinity; overall, no significant contributory family history has been reported. Prior genetic evaluation has included single-gene analysis performed on 2025-03-28, which was reported as negative.

Anthony Lopez is a 19-year-old male who presents for further evaluation of a complex neurodevelopmental phenotype characterized by structural brain differences, cognitive impairment, and seizure activity. He has a documented malformation of cortical development involving the cerebral hemispheres, noted on prior neuroimaging as abnormal cortical organization consistent with a congenital brain anomaly. Developmentally, he has longstanding cognitive delays with overall functioning in the mild intellectual disability range, requiring academic support services and assistance with activities that demand higher-level reasoning and adaptive skills. Neurologically, he has a history of recurrent seizure episodes without a clearly identified precipitating cause; events have been described as generalized convulsive episodes with postictal confusion, and he is followed by neurology for ongoing management. No additional systemic or metabolic abnormalities have been reported to date. Family history is noncontributory, with no known relatives affected by similar neurodevelopmental, neurological, or congenital conditions, and no known consanguinity. Prior genetic evaluation has included chromosomal microarray performed on 2025-09-01, which was reported as negative for pathogenic copy number changes.

William Flores (DOB 2015-02-12) is referred by Dr. Angela Thompson for further evaluation in the setting of multiple structural anomalies, cognitive and developmental concerns, and abnormal movement findings. Congenital renal malformation consistent with unilateral renal agenesis has been documented, with absence of one kidney on prior imaging and associated reduced overall renal mass, though without current need for renal replacement therapy; blood pressure and basic renal function have been monitored periodically. Developmental history is notable for significant delays in multiple domains, with functioning in the moderate intellectual disability range, including marked delays in expressive language, need for assistance with activities of daily living beyond what is expected for age, and requirement for individualized educational support services through school. Neurological examination and history are significant for abnormal involuntary movements characterized by intermittent dystonic posturing and abnormal muscle contractions affecting gait and fine motor control; these episodes are not clearly triggered by medications or metabolic derangements and have prompted ongoing neurologic follow-up. No additional systemic or metabolic abnormalities have been identified to date. Family history is reported as noncontributory, with no known similarly affected relatives and no known consanguinity between the parents. Prior genetic evaluation has included chromosomal microarray performed on 2024-12-31, which was reported as negative for pathogenic copy number changes.

Elizabeth Gonzalez is a 14-year-old female who presents for further evaluation due to a history of brain malformation of unspecified type, global developmental delay, and abnormal involuntary movements consistent with a dystonic movement disorder. Congenital structural abnormalities of the central nervous system were noted on prior neuroimaging in early childhood, with concerns for abnormal brain development and associated motor impairment. Developmentally, she has exhibited delays across multiple domains, including delayed attainment of early motor and language milestones and ongoing academic and adaptive challenges requiring special education services and school-based therapies. Neurologically, she has a history of sustained abnormal posturing and twisting movements affecting the upper and lower extremities, which are exacerbated by action and fatigue and have led to functional limitations in fine motor tasks and gait stability; there is no clear precipitating injury or secondary cause identified to date. Prior genetic evaluation has included chromosomal microarray analysis performed on 07/31/2025, which was reported as negative, without pathogenic copy number changes to explain her clinical presentation. No significant family history is reported, and there is no known parental consanguinity.

George Garcia is a 20-year-old male who presents for further evaluation of a complex medical history notable for multiple structural anomalies, significant cognitive impairment, and recurrent seizures. Congenital findings reported since infancy include a combination of dysmorphic features and other structural differences involving more than one organ system, raising concern for an underlying syndromic etiology. Developmentally, he has shown severe delays across domains, with markedly limited expressive and receptive language, need for assistance with most activities of daily living, and ongoing requirement for special education services with a highly supported classroom setting. His overall cognitive functioning is in the range consistent with severe intellectual impairment, and he has not achieved age-appropriate academic or adaptive milestones. Neurologically, he has a history of focal seizures that may secondarily generalize, with episodes characterized by loss of awareness, tonic stiffening, and occasional progression to bilateral convulsive activity; seizures have been described as intractable with breakthrough events despite treatment with multiple antiseizure medications and dose adjustments. No significant family history is reported, and there is no known consanguinity. Prior genetic evaluation includes chromosomal microarray performed on 2025-08-27, which was reported as negative.

Charles Anderson (DOB 2014-02-08) is referred by Dr. Robert Miller for evaluation of complex medical concerns, including multiple structural differences present since birth, significant developmental concerns, and abnormal movement symptoms. Congenital findings have included abnormalities of the feet consistent with positional and/or structural deformities noted in early childhood, for which he has been followed by orthopedics and physical therapy; these have impacted his gait and overall motor function. Developmentally, he has severe, generalized delay affecting multiple domains: he has marked limitation in cognitive functioning, requires extensive support for activities of daily living, and has significant delays in expressive and receptive language. Academic skills are substantially below age expectations, and he is in a highly supported educational setting with an individualized education plan. Neurologically, he has a history of abnormal involuntary movements characterized by intermittent, sustained muscle contractions and twisting postures involving the upper and lower extremities, with fluctuating severity over the course of the day; these episodes have prompted evaluation by pediatric neurology and trials of symptomatic medications with only partial benefit. There is no significant family history reported. Prior genetic evaluation has included chromosomal microarray performed on 2025-03-20, which was reported as negative.

Brian Sanchez is a 19-year-old male who presents with longstanding concerns for an autism spectrum condition characterized by persistent deficits in social communication and interaction, including limited eye contact, difficulty understanding social cues, and challenges with reciprocal conversation, as well as restricted, repetitive patterns of behavior such as insistence on routines, intense circumscribed interests, and sensory sensitivities. Behavioral observations have included episodes of unusual or socially inappropriate behaviors and emotional responses not proportionate to the situation, with occasional agitation and difficulty with transitions, leading to concerns about broader behavioral dysregulation. The patient also reports intermittent shortness of breath, described as brief episodes of feeling unable to take a full breath, occurring both at rest and with exertion, without clear precipitating factors or associated chest pain; no prior cardiopulmonary workup is documented in the chart. In addition, he has a history of recurrent headaches, typically bifrontal, of moderate intensity, occurring several times per week, sometimes associated with light sensitivity and difficulty concentrating, but without associated focal neurological deficits, visual changes, or recent head trauma. Family history is notable for a younger brother diagnosed in childhood with an autism spectrum condition and ongoing social-communication difficulties, and a paternal cousin reported to have significant learning and behavioral challenges requiring special education services, though no specific diagnosis is known; there is no known consanguinity. No prior genetic or metabolic testing is documented in the available records.

Anthony Walker is a 18-year-old individual who presents for evaluation with a history of intermittent chest pain and recurrent headaches. Chest pain has been described as substernal and sharp in quality, occurring episodically over the past several months, sometimes associated with mild exertion but without clear radiation, syncope, palpitations, or associated trauma. Symptoms have prompted prior outpatient evaluation, and current documentation is consistent with a working diagnosis of precordial pain of unclear etiology. In addition, Anthony reports frequent headaches, occurring several times per week, characterized as diffuse or frontal in location, of moderate intensity, and occasionally associated with light sensitivity and difficulty concentrating, but without focal neurologic deficits, visual loss, or recent head injury reported. No prior neuroimaging or cardiology workup is documented in the chart, and there is no record of prior genetic or metabolic testing. Review of systems is otherwise unremarkable based on available documentation. No significant family history is reported, including no known similarly affected relatives and no known consanguinity.

William Sanchez is a 5-year-old male who presents for evaluation of intermittent chest discomfort and respiratory symptoms. According to his caregiver, he has experienced several recent episodes of chest pain described as a mid-sternal, pressure-like sensation that occurs both at rest and with mild exertion, lasting several minutes at a time and resolving spontaneously without clear triggers. There is no associated syncope reported, but the discomfort has been concerning enough to limit his usual play activities on occasion. In addition, the caregiver reports episodes of shortness of breath, particularly with physical activity such as running or climbing stairs, during which William appears winded sooner than peers and needs to rest to catch his breath; these episodes are not accompanied by audible wheezing at home, and there is no history of nocturnal awakenings due to breathing difficulty. He has also had recurrent headaches over the past several months, described as frontal or generalized in location, occurring several times per week, sometimes associated with irritability and a preference for a dark, quiet room. The headaches are variably responsive to over-the-counter analgesics, and there is no history of visual changes, focal weakness, or seizure-like activity reported. No prior diagnostic testing or imaging related to these symptoms is documented in the chart, and no previous genetic or metabolic evaluations are noted. Family history is reviewed and is not contributory; no significant family history is reported, and there is no known parental consanguinity.

Timothy Jones (DOB 2005-03-25) is evaluated today for cardiopulmonary and neurologic symptoms. He reports intermittent central chest discomfort characterized as a pressure sensation without clear exertional trigger, for which prior emergency evaluations have been unrevealing to date; symptoms are consistent with a history of precordial chest pain. He also describes recurrent episodes of shortness of breath, particularly with moderate activity and occasionally at rest, associated with a sensation of not being able to take a full breath but without documented wheezing, hemoptysis, or syncope; no prior cardiology or pulmonology workup is documented in the chart. In addition, there is a history of unilateral weakness affecting the right side, with fluctuating severity and episodic difficulty with fine motor tasks in the right hand and intermittent dragging of the right leg; no clear precipitating trauma is noted, and prior neuroimaging, if performed, is not available in the current record. No prior genetic or other specialized diagnostic testing is documented. Family history is reviewed and is notable for no significant familial disorders, with no known consanguinity reported.

Patricia Adams is a female patient born 12/28/2007 who presents with intermittent chest discomfort and associated respiratory symptoms. She reports episodes of substernal chest pain occurring over the past several weeks, described as a pressure or tightness sensation that is sometimes exacerbated by exertion and occasionally at rest. The pain has prompted concern for possible cardiac or pulmonary etiology. She also endorses shortness of breath, particularly with moderate physical activity such as climbing stairs or brisk walking, and at times feels unable to take a full deep breath. Symptoms have not been clearly associated with cough, fever, or recent respiratory infection based on current documentation. In addition, she has experienced recurrent headaches of unspecified type, with variable intensity, sometimes requiring rest in a dark room and over-the-counter analgesics for relief; no consistent visual aura, focal neurologic deficits, or clear triggers are recorded. There is no documentation of prior diagnostic evaluations related to these symptoms, and no previous relevant laboratory or imaging test results are available in the chart. Family history is noted as noncontributory, with no significant hereditary conditions or similar symptoms reported among close relatives.

Anthony White (DOB: 10/21/2020) is an intersex pediatric patient who presents for evaluation in the setting of intermittent chest symptoms. Caregiver reports episodes of chest discomfort described as central chest pain occurring over the past several weeks, sometimes noted at rest and occasionally with mild exertion, without clear precipitating trauma or recent respiratory infection. The pain is variably described as pressure-like and sometimes sharp, lasting several minutes before resolving spontaneously, and has not been associated with syncope, palpitations, or cyanosis. In addition, the caregiver notes intermittent shortness of breath characterized by increased work of breathing and the child “breathing fast” during play and at night, occasionally requiring the child to stop activity to rest. There is no associated wheezing reported, and no prior diagnosis of asthma or cardiac disease has been documented. No prior genetic or other specialized diagnostic testing is recorded in the chart. No significant family history is reported.

Michael Nelson is a 6-year-old male who presents for evaluation due to concerns for autism spectrum–type behaviors and associated developmental and behavioral issues. Parents report longstanding social communication difficulties, including limited eye contact, reduced reciprocal conversation, and challenges engaging in age-appropriate peer interactions. He exhibits restricted interests and repetitive behaviors, such as intense preoccupation with specific topics and a strong need for routines, with significant distress when these are disrupted. Behavioral concerns include impulsivity, difficulty sustaining attention, and challenges with self-regulation that have affected his functioning at home and in school. There is a history of delayed acquisition of social and adaptive skills, and teachers have noted problems with classroom participation and following multi-step instructions. No prior genetic or metabolic testing results are available in the record. Family history is notable for a maternal younger brother diagnosed in early childhood with autism spectrum–type developmental and social communication difficulties requiring special education services. A paternal first cousin reportedly has significant learning difficulties and behavioral concerns consistent with attention and concentration problems, currently managed with school-based supports. Parents report that Michael’s parents are second cousins, with shared grandparents on one side of the family. Additional family history includes a maternal grandmother with long-standing osteoarthritis requiring joint replacement in her 60s and a paternal uncle with seasonal allergic rhinitis; these relatives are otherwise healthy. No other significant hereditary conditions have been documented.
